wiki.text:
A 'methyl group' is an alkyl derived from methane, containing one carbon atom
bonded to three hydrogen atoms — CH<sub>3</sub>. The group is often abbreviated
'Me'. Such hydrocarbon groups occur in many organic compounds. While the methyl
group is usually part of a larger molecule, it can be found on its own in either
of three forms: anion, cation or radical. The anion has eight valence electrons,
the radical seven and the cation six. All three forms are highly reactive and
rarely observed.<ref></ref>
